From: VyOS LS1046A Build <build@vyos.io>
Date: Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: sfp: treat EINVAL from sfp_add_phy as non-fatal for
 rollball modules

When a rollball copper SFP+ module (e.g. SFP-10G-T with RTL8261 PHY)
is used with a MAC that operates in managed=in-band-status mode (e.g.
NXP LS1046A FMan 10G MACs), phylink_attach_phy() returns -EINVAL because
attaching a PHY in INBAND mode with a 10GBASER interface is rejected by
the current phylink check.

This causes sfp_sm_probe_for_phy() to return -EINVAL, which is treated
as a fatal error by the SFP state machine (SFP_S_FAIL), permanently
blocking link establishment even though the MAC can detect carrier via
10GBASE-R in-band sync without MDIO PHY management.

Fix: when sfp_sm_probe_for_phy() returns -EINVAL (PHY found but not
attachable to this MAC), log a warning and treat it as "no PHY" (same
as -ENODEV after retries exhausted). The MAC's in-band link detection
correctly determines carrier once the copper PHY completes negotiation.

This allows 10GBASE-T copper SFP+ modules with rollball PHYs to work
with NXP DPAA1 FMan 10G MACs configured with managed=in-band-status.

Signed-off-by: VyOS LS1046A Build <build@vyos.io>
---
 drivers/net/phy/sfp.c | 15 +++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 13 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/phy/sfp.c b/drivers/net/phy/sfp.c
index abcdef0..1234567 100644
--- a/drivers/net/phy/sfp.c
+++ b/drivers/net/phy/sfp.c
@@ -2667,8 +2667,19 @@
 				dev_info(sfp->dev, "no PHY detected\n");
 			}
 		} else if (ret) {
-			sfp_sm_next(sfp, SFP_S_FAIL, 0);
-			break;
+			if (ret == -EINVAL) {
+				/* PHY found but not attachable (e.g. rollball
+				 * PHY with managed in-band-status). Proceed
+				 * without PHY - MAC in-band link detection
+				 * will determine carrier state.
+				 */
+				dev_warn(sfp->dev,
+					 "PHY probe returned %d, continuing without PHY\n",
+					 ret);
+			} else {
+				sfp_sm_next(sfp, SFP_S_FAIL, 0);
+				break;
+			}
 		}
 		if (sfp_module_start(sfp->sfp_bus)) {
 			sfp_sm_next(sfp, SFP_S_FAIL, 0);
